                id = "rosetta", speaker = "Mistress Ekko",
                text = "*(She freezes, the scholar in her seeing it a half-second before the woman dares to.)* ...The Rosetta. *(very quietly.)* Your name is the *key* to the whole Wall. Teach you the dead tongue, and you could read *every* name carved into it — eleven thousand, ten thousand years of the Faithless, every one *legible* at last. *(she grips the scroll, trembling.)* They were never *anonymous*, Returned — that's the lie. The Wall *named* them, in this dead tongue, so precisely that no living reader could ever decode it and grieve them properly. The *forgetting* was *enforced by illiteracy.* *(she looks at you, fierce now.)* Then yes. *Yes.* I'll teach you. Not for your one name — for *all* of them. You'll be the first soul in ten thousand years who can stand before the Wall and *read it aloud.* Name by name. *(her sixty years of solitary rooms blaze into purpose.)* I kept this dead tongue alive in a lonely room, and I never knew *why*, and *this* is why — so that when the one who returns came, there'd be someone left who could teach him to *read the dead their own names.* Sit. We've ten thousand years of vocabulary and not a moment to waste.",
