            {
                id = "author", speaker = "Magister Cole",
                text = "*(He freezes — the one question a textual scholar cannot wave away.)* Who *authorized* the edits. *(quietly.)* The provenance. The *editorial authority.* *(he flips through his apparatus, and his certainty curdles as he fails to find it.)* I — the Wall's deletions are attributed to... *(he searches)* ...to *no one.* There is no colophon. No editor's mark. No authorizing hand. The Faithless were cut from the text by an edit with *no recorded editor.* *(he looks up, white.)* In textual scholarship, Returned, an emendation with no authority is not a *correction.* It is *vandalism.* A later hand defacing the manuscript and *claiming* it was always thus. *(he sets down the red pen as if it burns.)* I have spent my life enforcing the readings of an *anonymous vandal* and calling it the original text. *(quietly, devastated.)* Show me the manuscript before the deletions, you said. *I cannot find it.* Someone *destroyed the base text.* And a scholar who's lost the base text has only one ethical move left: trust the *recovered* readings over the *received* ones. Which means trusting *you.* Gods. I need to lie down. The whole edition is compromised.",
